The electrochemical behaviour of DOX with different concentrations (0.1–10 µM) was also examined on the CDs-5.0/MgO/SPCE using 0.1 (M) PBS as supporting electrolyte at pH-5. The cyclic voltammograms (Fig. 8
                        a) showed that the anodic peak current values were increased with increasing DOX concentrations at the modified electrode surface. As in Fig. 8b, a linear relationship was obtained between the oxidation peak current intensity (Ipa) and DOX concentrations at low concentration (0.1–1 µM) only, and the corresponding linear regression equation is expressed as y = 1.118x + 2.352 with a correlation coefficient (R2) = 0.99 (Fig. 8b). The limit of detection (LOD) of DOX was 0.09 µM calculated from the equation (3) s/m, where s represents the standard deviation of the anodic peak current and m represents the slope of the calibration curve. The limit of quantification (LOQ) value was 0.297 µM (Table 2
                        ).
